default  The list is not intended to be exhaustive, and inevitably each community group will encounter its own particular challenges:
defaultPlease see Appendix A for a more detailed analysis of the 
defaultspecific challenges 
defaultfaced by community energy groups seeking finance
default.   This
default highlights 
defaulta number of issues which community groups must address to secure appropriate funding.
defaultOne of the primary barriers to the expansion of community energy to the levels achieved in Germany is the difficulty that these projects have in accessing conventional finance while retaining community ownership.
defaultMost debt providers are unwilling to finance community energy projects
default,
default and even those who have a commitment to community energy are reluctant to provide funding for projects below the £2-5 million level.
defaultThis 
defaultwould leave private equity as the only other 
defaultconventional financing route for smaller projects. 
default 
defaultThis cuts out community ownership and means that financial benefits do not accrue for community benefit.
defaultThis explains why smaller-scale community energy projects to date have been funded exclusively through a combination of local equity and social finance, i.e. grants, debt or equity on preferential terms.
defaultPure Leapfrog aims to overcome this barrier by acting as an “aggregator” of smaller projects, bundling them up into portfolios of sufficient size and with the right risk/return profile for conventional finance. 
defaultS
defaultuccess 
defaultin aggregation can 
defaultunlock hundreds of millions of pounds of capital to fund community energy, transforming the demand for community-based renewables and making a major impact on the UK social investment market.
defaultIn order to get to a situation where individual projects, with different owners, technologies and locations can be aggregated effectively for commercial investment, there are a number of hurdles to overcome:
default1)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultReduce origination and transaction costs
defaultOrigination and transaction costs for community energy projects are too high to make conventional debt provision viable because the projects are small and they often move at a slow and erratic pace.
default2)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultDevelop risk management techniques appropriate for community energy
defaultFunders often do not know how to (cost effectively) evaluate the credit-worthiness of community based organisations, which may lack a balance sheet or trading history, but are underpinned by community support.  Conventional techniques for reducing risk, e.g. expensive due diligence and insurance, are not appropriate for community-based projects.
default3)
default&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; 
defaultCollaborating with, and providing support to, community energy groups
defaultIn order to accelerate the growth of community energy, time and expertise 
defaultneeds to be invested 
defaultinto community energy groups to build capacity of groups to engage their communities, manage project development and raise funding, both in the form of community shares and debt.  
